// Noise Analysis Example
// NMOS: gm=1mA/V, T=300K, BW=10MHz
// k = 1.38×10⁻²³ J/K

// Input-referred thermal noise power density:
// Svin = 4kT×(2/3)/gm
//      = 4 × 1.38e-23 × 300 × 0.667 / 1e-3
//      = 4 × 1.38e-23 × 300 × 667
//      = 1.104×10⁻¹⁷ V²/Hz
//      = 11.04 nV/√Hz

// RMS noise voltage over 10MHz bandwidth:
// Vn_rms = √(Svin × BW)
//        = √(1.104e-17 × 10e6)
//        = √(1.104e-10)
//        = 10.5 μV rms

// To halve input-referred noise:
// Double gm → requires 4× current or 4× W/L
// Trade-off: noise vs power vs area

// Friis Formula Example — Two-Stage Amplifier
// Stage 1: G1=20dB=100, NF1=3dB=2 (linear)
// Stage 2: G2=10dB=10,  NF2=6dB=4 (linear)

// Total noise factor (linear):
// F_total = F1 + (F2-1)/G1
//         = 2 + (4-1)/100
//         = 2 + 0.03
//         = 2.03

// Total NF:
// NF_total = 10×log10(2.03) = 3.07 dB
// Nearly equal to stage 1 alone (3dB)!
// Stage 2 contributes only 0.07dB → first stage dominates

// If stage 1 gain is reduced to G1=10dB=10:
// F_total = 2 + (4-1)/10 = 2 + 0.3 = 2.3
// NF = 3.62 dB — stage 2 contributes 0.62dB

// Key insight: maximize first-stage gain to minimize NF
// But: high gain reduces dynamic range and linearity
// Design trade-off common in RF/sensor amplifiers

