// ADC Performance Calculation
// 12-bit SAR ADC, Vref=1.8V, fs=1Msps

// Resolution:
// 1 LSB = 1.8V / 2^12 = 1.8V / 4096 = 439 μV/LSB

// Ideal SNR (12-bit):
// SNR = 6.02×12 + 1.76 = 72.24 + 1.76 = 74 dB

// If measured SNR = 70 dB:
// ENOB = (70 - 1.76)/6.02 = 68.24/6.02 = 11.34 bits
// ADC behaves like 11.34-bit ideal ADC

// Nyquist limit:
// Max input frequency = fs/2 = 500 kHz

// Power figure of merit (FoM):
// FoM = Power / (2^ENOB × fs)  [J/conversion]
// Lower is better — state-of-art ≈ 1-10 fJ/conv

// 4-bit SAR ADC Conversion
// Vref=1.6V, Vin=0.9V, LSB=1.6/16=0.1V

// Step 1: Try MSB (bit 3) = 1 → DAC=1.6/2=0.8V
// Compare: Vin=0.9V > DAC=0.8V → KEEP bit3=1
// Code so far: 1000 (0.8V)

// Step 2: Try bit 2 = 1 → DAC=0.8+0.4=1.2V
// Compare: Vin=0.9V < DAC=1.2V → CLEAR bit2=0
// Code so far: 1000 (0.8V)

// Step 3: Try bit 1 = 1 → DAC=0.8+0.2=1.0V
// Compare: Vin=0.9V < DAC=1.0V → CLEAR bit1=0
// Code so far: 1000 (0.8V)

// Step 4: Try bit 0 = 1 → DAC=0.8+0.1=0.9V
