// INTERVIEW REFERENCE: Source Degeneration
// CS amplifier with Rs in source
// Gain with degeneration:
// Av = -gm×RD / (1 + gm×Rs)
// ≈ -RD/Rs for gm×Rs >> 1
//
// Input resistance increases: Rin_eff = (1+gm×Rs)/gm
// Bandwidth increases (less Miller)
// Noise figure increases (signal path has gain <1)
//
// INTERVIEW REFERENCE: Cascode Amplifier
// CS (M1) + CG (M2) stacked
// Gain: Av = -gm1 × Rout_cascode
// Rout_cascode = gm2×ro2×ro1 (from bottom)
// High gain due to high output impedance
// Eliminates Miller effect → higher bandwidth
//
// INTERVIEW REFERENCE: Feedback
// Shunt-shunt feedback (transresistance amp):
// Rout_closed = Rout_open / (1 + T)
// Rin_closed = Rin_open / (1 + T)
// Gain_closed = A/(1+Aβ) ≈ 1/β for Aβ>>1

// Q1: CS with degeneration (Rs=1/gm)
// Av = -gm×RD/(1+gm×Rs) = -gm×RD/(1+1) = -gm×RD/2
// Gain halved, but bandwidth and linearity improved

// Q2: Cascode eliminates Miller effect
// CS: Cgd appears as Cgd(1+|Av|) at input → small bandwidth
// Cascode: M2 presents low impedance at M1 drain
// Vdrain_M1 is nearly constant → Cgd effect reduced
// Result: bandwidth ~ 10× higher than CS alone

// Q3: Feedback benefits
// Closed-loop gain: A_cl = A/(1+Aβ) ≈ 1/β (precise)
// Output impedance: Rout_cl = Rout/(1+Aβ) (lower)
// Input impedance: Rin_cl = Rin×(1+Aβ) (higher, for series)
// Distortion: THD_cl = THD/(1+Aβ) (reduced)
// Bandwidth: BW_cl = BW×(1+Aβ) (extended)

// Q4: GBW limited by compensation cap Cc
// GBW = gm1/(2π×Cc)
// Increasing gm1 (more current): increases GBW but more power
// Decreasing Cc: increases GBW but reduces phase margin
// Trade-off: GBW vs PM vs power vs slew rate

// Q5: 1mA mirror with 1% accuracy
// σ(ΔI/I) = A/√(WL) = 1%
// If A≈0.05 (μm) from Pelgrom:
// √(WL) = 0.05/0.01 = 5 → WL = 25μm²
// Use cascode to reduce systematic error from VDS mismatch

